1
00:00:02,260 --> 00:00:02,950
Speaker 12: Hi, everyone.

2
00:00:03,480 --> 00:00:04,919
My name is Shadi Riafi.

3
00:00:04,919 --> 00:00:09,390
I'm a senior software developer
at fullinfo.com, and this talk is

4
00:00:09,390 --> 00:00:13,699
about building an MCP server in
Go for a real, uh, B2B workflow.

5
00:00:14,749 --> 00:00:19,020
The specific case I'll use in i- is a
company intelligence platform built on

6
00:00:19,020 --> 00:00:21,210
more than one million company profiles.

7
00:00:21,850 --> 00:00:27,520
The goal was to let an LLM client help
the, with real workflow task, such

8
00:00:27,520 --> 00:00:32,409
as searching for companies, looking
for company details, and working with

9
00:00:32,409 --> 00:00:37,200
collections without turning the LLM into
unsafe bridge into production systems.

10
00:00:38,380 --> 00:00:43,330
The stack behind the talk is Go,
MCP, GraphQL, and AWS AppSync.

11
00:00:44,450 --> 00:00:47,319
The main point is not only
how to connect these pieces.

12
00:00:47,420 --> 00:00:50,430
The more important point is how
to keep the interface narrow,

13
00:00:51,110 --> 00:00:55,580
testable, observable, and safe
enough for real business data.

14
00:00:57,819 --> 00:01:02,920
Um, most MCP examples stop where
a demo becomes interesting.

15
00:01:03,699 --> 00:01:08,640
A demo usually proves that a model
can call a tool, get a result, and

16
00:01:08,640 --> 00:01:10,960
show the result back to the user.

17
00:01:11,979 --> 00:01:14,839
That is useful, but
it's only the beginning.

18
00:01:16,290 --> 00:01:20,800
The harder question is what happens
when the integration touch, touches

19
00:01:20,890 --> 00:01:26,249
real business data, real workflows,
and real operational constraints.

20
00:01:27,169 --> 00:01:32,989
At that point, a thin API
path through is not enough.

21
00:01:34,430 --> 00:01:36,450
Broad tools become hard to validate.

22
00:01:37,230 --> 00:01:39,689
Prompt-level guardrails are not enough.

23
00:01:40,640 --> 00:01:44,919
And if there is a little visibility,
it becomes difficult to know what

24
00:01:44,919 --> 00:01:46,289
the system is actually doing.

25
00:01:48,350 --> 00:01:53,619
So to read it, the MCP server as a
production interface, that means narrow

26
00:01:53,619 --> 00:01:57,080
contracts, a clear read and write split.

27
00:01:58,750 --> 00:02:02,250
Backend authentication preserved,
and tests and logs that make

28
00:02:02,250 --> 00:02:03,550
behavior understandable.

29
00:02:07,870 --> 00:02:10,199
The user-facing workflow is simple.

30
00:02:10,729 --> 00:02:16,020
A user might ask a question like,
"Find a SaaS companies in Germany with

31
00:02:16,020 --> 00:02:21,340
fifty to th- to one hundred employees."
But the server should not pass the

32
00:02:21,340 --> 00:02:23,269
raw sentence directly into GraphQL.

33
00:02:23,959 --> 00:02:29,349
Instead, the LLM client selects a tool, in
this case, search companies, for example.

34
00:02:30,570 --> 00:02:35,130
The MCP server validates the inputs,
normalizes them, and shapes the request.

35
00:02:35,490 --> 00:02:39,269
And only then does it call GraphQL
through AppSync behind the authentication.

36
00:02:41,850 --> 00:02:45,679
The result comes back as flat
company summarize, summaries, not

37
00:02:45,679 --> 00:02:47,540
as a raw nested backend response.

38
00:02:48,900 --> 00:02:50,299
The separation is important.

39
00:02:51,089 --> 00:02:56,759
User requests are normalized into explicit
tool calls, and the MCP server never pass

40
00:02:56,759 --> 00:02:59,319
raw user input directly to the GraphQL.

41
00:03:03,689 --> 00:03:05,859
This is the architecture at high level.

42
00:03:07,609 --> 00:03:13,570
Like Cloud or another MCP client,
whatever, handles, handles the

43
00:03:13,570 --> 00:03:15,270
user intent and tool selection.

44
00:03:16,650 --> 00:03:20,759
The Go MCP server sits in the middle
and acts as a contract enforcing layer.

45
00:03:21,410 --> 00:03:26,789
It uses MCP Go for dispatch,
schemas, validation, mutation,

46
00:03:27,849 --> 00:03:29,650
gating, and response shaping.

47
00:03:31,590 --> 00:03:36,540
Behind that, AWS AppSync
remains the GraphQL boundary

48
00:03:36,570 --> 00:03:37,969
into a s- business backend.

49
00:03:38,820 --> 00:03:42,930
The company intelligence platform
stays the system of record.

50
00:03:43,550 --> 00:03:46,480
Cloud never talks to GraphQL directly.

51
00:03:48,349 --> 00:03:51,239
This distinction matters
more than protocol itself.

52
00:03:52,140 --> 00:03:57,550
MCP provides the connection model,
but the production question is how

53
00:03:57,550 --> 00:04:01,040
much power each tool gets and how
precisely its behavior is defined.

54
00:04:06,410 --> 00:04:09,479
Authentication is also part
of the server boundary.

55
00:04:10,959 --> 00:04:14,880
The server can authenticate to
AppSync with OIDC bearer token

56
00:04:15,039 --> 00:04:19,560
and app key or AWS Sigv4 signing.

57
00:04:19,859 --> 00:04:25,860
Depending on the environment, AppSync
is AWS managed GraphQL gateway, so

58
00:04:25,860 --> 00:04:29,850
the query body stays standard GraphQL
while the auth headers vary by mode.

59
00:04:31,530 --> 00:04:36,200
For the production-oriented path, OIDC
is, is the important model because token

60
00:04:36,200 --> 00:04:38,640
carries user id-- us- user identity.

61
00:04:39,839 --> 00:04:43,469
The LM client is acting on behalf
of the user or of a specific user,

62
00:04:43,670 --> 00:04:45,230
not as a generic service account.

63
00:04:49,780 --> 00:04:54,300
That means backend authorization,
audit trails, and data scoping

64
00:04:54,300 --> 00:04:59,380
work the same way they would if the
user were calling the API directly.

65
00:05:01,049 --> 00:05:05,259
The MCP layer does not bypass or weaken
the existing access model, it inherits

66
00:05:07,849 --> 00:05:07,909
it.

67
00:05:07,909 --> 00:05:09,489
Uh, the practical rule is simple.

68
00:05:09,589 --> 00:05:13,439
Keep credentials and signing inside
the MCP server boundary and let

69
00:05:13,439 --> 00:05:15,519
AppSync enforce backend authorization.

70
00:05:20,530 --> 00:05:23,770
The implementation defines nine
tools, and eight are exposed

71
00:05:23,770 --> 00:05:25,070
in the shipped configuration.

72
00:05:26,619 --> 00:05:30,119
The read-only tools cover the
company search, single company

73
00:05:30,119 --> 00:05:34,100
lookup, batch lookup, AI-assisted
search, lis- listing collections,

74
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:36,109
and reading collections items.

75
00:05:37,289 --> 00:05:40,390
The exposed mutation-capable
tools are added to collection

76
00:05:40,390 --> 00:05:42,189
and request e- email discovery.

77
00:05:43,650 --> 00:05:46,480
These are right-side actions,
so they are handled differently.

78
00:05:47,679 --> 00:05:54,470
The ninth tool cre-- the ninth tool,
Create Collection was implemented

79
00:05:54,470 --> 00:06:00,194
but not exposed One tool was
held back and slide 15 shows why.

80
00:06:01,645 --> 00:06:05,125
It passed mocked unit level tests,
but when validated against the real

81
00:06:05,125 --> 00:06:10,224
backend through MCP inspector, it
revealed a lambda null pointer failure.

82
00:06:10,575 --> 00:06:13,695
The release choice was to keep
the implementation but remove

83
00:06:13,695 --> 00:06:16,464
the tool from registration until
the backend issue was fixed.

84
00:06:17,695 --> 00:06:21,445
This is a good example why real
system validation must remain

85
00:06:21,585 --> 00:06:22,804
part of the release gate.

86
00:06:27,784 --> 00:06:31,193
The separation between read and
write starts in the registry.

87
00:06:33,395 --> 00:06:37,084
Read-only tools are constructed
without the mutation flag because

88
00:06:37,084 --> 00:06:39,044
they have no mutation path to gate.

89
00:06:39,964 --> 00:06:43,914
Mutation-capable tools receive
the explicit allow mutations flag.

90
00:06:45,135 --> 00:06:47,385
This makes the design
easier to reason about.

91
00:06:47,574 --> 00:06:52,205
A read-only tool is simpler to review,
simpler to test, and simpler to observe

92
00:06:52,304 --> 00:06:54,314
because it expresses one kind of intent.

93
00:06:55,484 --> 00:06:59,074
It cannot accidentally become
a write path because mutation

94
00:06:59,074 --> 00:07:00,775
capability was never passed into it.

95
00:07:01,965 --> 00:07:05,175
For mutation tools, the flag
becomes an operational switch.

96
00:07:05,825 --> 00:07:08,715
Without it, the tool fails
before doing any backend work.

97
00:07:13,454 --> 00:07:17,525
For the read path, the important point
is that validation, execution, and

98
00:07:17,525 --> 00:07:19,755
shaping are handled by distinct layers.

99
00:07:21,735 --> 00:07:24,974
The tool starts with a row
arguments from the MCP call.

100
00:07:25,604 --> 00:07:30,485
Those are passed into type parameters,
validation checks required, fields.

101
00:07:31,165 --> 00:07:34,585
Normalization handles things
like trimming input, resolving

102
00:07:34,585 --> 00:07:36,384
country codes, and capping limits.

103
00:07:37,415 --> 00:07:41,675
Then the tool builds a GraphQL variables
map and calls the AppSync client.

104
00:07:43,024 --> 00:07:48,684
After the GraphQL returns, the response
is flattened into a public result type

105
00:07:48,684 --> 00:07:50,645
before it goes back to the LLM client.

106
00:07:51,395 --> 00:07:55,544
So the MCP server never passes raw
user input directly to GraphQL.

107
00:07:56,625 --> 00:07:59,645
And it never returns raw
GraphQL responses to the client.

108
00:08:04,775 --> 00:08:07,624
Scale changes the behavior
of even simple tools.

109
00:08:08,125 --> 00:08:10,825
This platform has more than 1
million companies' profiles.

110
00:08:11,064 --> 00:08:15,095
A broad query can produce results that
are technically valid but not useful.

111
00:08:16,374 --> 00:08:18,855
So the search tool had to
be bounded from the start.

112
00:08:20,174 --> 00:08:23,535
For example, if the user does not
provide a limit, default is 10.

113
00:08:24,004 --> 00:08:29,084
If the user asks for more than 100
results, the server cap it at 100.

114
00:08:29,724 --> 00:08:31,715
Country inputs are normalized too.

115
00:08:31,824 --> 00:08:36,815
So DE becomes a backend value for
Germany and US becomes the backend

116
00:08:36,815 --> 00:08:38,194
value for the United States.

117
00:08:39,995 --> 00:08:44,304
Even with a hard limit of 100
results, broad requests can be too

118
00:08:44,304 --> 00:08:48,385
broad to be useful and can compound
through follow-up queries that

119
00:08:48,385 --> 00:08:52,365
where normalization is a production
concern, not just a convenience.

120
00:08:57,110 --> 00:09:00,490
The backend GraphQL response is
naturally shaped for the backend

121
00:09:00,490 --> 00:09:02,539
domain, not for the LLM client.

122
00:09:03,360 --> 00:09:07,459
For example, company data can be
nested under company model, company

123
00:09:07,539 --> 00:09:09,289
description, and text fields.

124
00:09:10,150 --> 00:09:13,580
That might be fine inside the
service boundary, but it's not the

125
00:09:13,580 --> 00:09:15,310
best shape to return to a model.

126
00:09:16,500 --> 00:09:21,109
So the tool returns a consint-
consistently shaped record, ID,

127
00:09:21,259 --> 00:09:25,009
name, country, employee range,
domain, and industry text.

128
00:09:25,670 --> 00:09:29,089
For search and retrieval
tools, explicit conversion

129
00:09:29,089 --> 00:09:30,560
functions handle the flattening.

130
00:09:32,770 --> 00:09:36,730
This reduces accidental field
confusion for the LLM client.

131
00:09:37,190 --> 00:09:42,579
It also makes the testing easier because
the output contract is stable and narrow.

132
00:09:47,780 --> 00:09:50,240
Mutation safety uses a default deny model.

133
00:09:51,739 --> 00:09:55,300
The add to collection tool checks
whether mutations are allowed before it

134
00:09:55,300 --> 00:09:57,899
validates fields or class calls GraphQL.

135
00:09:59,199 --> 00:10:03,490
If that flag is not enabled, it returns
a clear error, mutations are disabled.

136
00:10:03,769 --> 00:10:05,189
Use the allowMutations flag.

137
00:10:06,960 --> 00:10:10,740
This is a full... It is not
a full authorization model.

138
00:10:10,849 --> 00:10:14,070
Backend authorization still belongs
in the backend, but it is an

139
00:10:14,070 --> 00:10:16,009
effective operational control point.

140
00:10:16,779 --> 00:10:21,819
It forces the team to make deliberate
decision about whether write paths

141
00:10:21,819 --> 00:10:23,940
are available in a given environment.

142
00:10:27,319 --> 00:10:28,940
It changes the default question.

143
00:10:29,020 --> 00:10:33,420
Instead of asking, "Why not let the client
write?" The team has to answer, "What

144
00:10:33,509 --> 00:10:35,950
evidence make these writes paths safe?"

145
00:10:41,230 --> 00:10:45,139
The mutation gate was
developed test first.

146
00:10:46,199 --> 00:10:51,449
The test constructs the add to collection
tool with mutation disabled, calls

147
00:10:51,449 --> 00:10:53,659
execute, and then assert three things.

148
00:10:53,930 --> 00:10:59,379
It expects an error, it expects no result,
and most importantly, it asserts that

149
00:10:59,379 --> 00:11:01,200
the mock GraphQL client was never called.

150
00:11:02,809 --> 00:11:05,079
The last assertion is
the real safety check.

151
00:11:05,739 --> 00:11:10,049
It proves the guard happens
before any backend execution path.

152
00:11:11,049 --> 00:11:13,279
This is the TDD loop in practice.

153
00:11:13,279 --> 00:11:16,520
Failing test, guard
implementation, passing assertion.

154
00:11:17,470 --> 00:11:21,520
The value is not just the code works, the
value is that the contract is preserved

155
00:11:21,599 --> 00:11:26,090
by a test that will fail if someone later
moves the GraphQL call before the gate.

156
00:11:30,770 --> 00:11:33,170
This is also where Go helped.

157
00:11:34,410 --> 00:11:39,780
The MCP layer introduces its own
failure modes, weak validation,

158
00:11:40,030 --> 00:11:44,660
unclear tool semantics, poor error
handling, or mismatches between tool

159
00:11:44,660 --> 00:11:46,390
behavior and backend assumption.

160
00:11:47,749 --> 00:11:51,530
Go's ordinary server Service
patterns made those boundaries

161
00:11:51,609 --> 00:11:53,360
explicit instead of magical.

162
00:11:57,019 --> 00:12:00,390
The interface shown here
is deliberately small.

163
00:12:00,629 --> 00:12:05,679
Execute takes a context, a query string,
a variable map, and a result point.

164
00:12:09,569 --> 00:12:14,439
That context can carry cancellation and
deadlines into the AppSync HTTP call.

165
00:12:14,769 --> 00:12:18,080
The same small client interface
supports mock tool tests

166
00:12:18,360 --> 00:12:19,870
and real AppSync execution.

167
00:12:21,170 --> 00:12:22,719
Type parameters also matter.

168
00:12:22,849 --> 00:12:27,110
The tool handler parses raw MCP arguments
before building GraphQL variables.

169
00:12:27,960 --> 00:12:33,530
That gives tests a clean place to check
validation, normalization, and request

170
00:12:33,530 --> 00:12:36,060
shape before the backend is touched.

171
00:12:42,019 --> 00:12:46,309
Mock tests become... Mock tests
became much more valuable once

172
00:12:46,309 --> 00:12:49,650
they captured the actual GraphQL
variables sent by each tool.

173
00:12:50,980 --> 00:12:56,230
In this example, the mock records
the variable pa-path to execute.

174
00:12:56,840 --> 00:13:02,689
After the tool runs, the test can check
the limit capping happening, the country

175
00:13:02,689 --> 00:13:07,699
code resolution happened, and that
the backend variable shape is correct.

176
00:13:09,490 --> 00:13:14,310
This matters because bugs in normalization
are easy to miss if the tests only

177
00:13:14,310 --> 00:13:16,729
check the resu-result come back.

178
00:13:18,240 --> 00:13:21,039
A mock response can make the
test pass even when the tool

179
00:13:21,039 --> 00:13:22,339
send the wrong variables.

180
00:13:23,289 --> 00:13:26,760
By capturing the result, a request
shape, the test checks the contract

181
00:13:26,760 --> 00:13:31,499
between m-the MCP layer and, and the
AppSync, not only in the final response.

182
00:13:37,239 --> 00:13:41,060
Mocked unit tests cannot substitute
for validation against the real system.

183
00:13:41,440 --> 00:13:43,500
The best example was createCollection.

184
00:13:44,929 --> 00:13:49,349
At the unit level, the tool behavior
looked fine, but the MCP ex-inspector

185
00:13:49,349 --> 00:13:54,300
let us, let us issue tool calls over
STD before involving the LLM client.

186
00:13:55,550 --> 00:13:58,800
Against the real AppSync
endpoint, they revealed a backend

187
00:13:58,800 --> 00:14:00,190
Lambda null pointer failure.

188
00:14:01,999 --> 00:14:05,839
The release decision was straightforward:
keep the code, but not register

189
00:14:05,839 --> 00:14:07,599
the tool in the ship configuration.

190
00:14:08,419 --> 00:14:11,699
That is the kind of failure that
a mock is not expected to catch.

191
00:14:11,899 --> 00:14:13,550
The lesson is not that mocks are bad.

192
00:14:13,879 --> 00:14:18,079
The lesson is that mock tests and real
system validation answer different

193
00:14:18,079 --> 00:14:20,120
questions and are bo-and both are needed.

194
00:14:24,989 --> 00:14:29,950
Rate limited-- limiting also
needed upfront design because LLM

195
00:14:29,950 --> 00:14:31,709
workflows are conver-conversational.

196
00:14:32,679 --> 00:14:36,569
A user might ask a question, then
ask a follow-up, then refine again.

197
00:14:36,870 --> 00:14:39,389
A model may make several
tools calls in a short period.

198
00:14:40,239 --> 00:14:43,179
If the tool is expensive,
the loop can become a backend

199
00:14:43,179 --> 00:14:44,620
protection issue very quickly.

200
00:14:45,659 --> 00:14:50,179
So AI search is limited to five
requests per minute Request email

201
00:14:50,179 --> 00:14:53,579
discovery is limited to ten requests
per hour because it represents a

202
00:14:53,579 --> 00:14:55,220
more expensive write set operation.

203
00:14:58,430 --> 00:15:01,350
These limits are not only backend
protection, they are also LLM

204
00:15:01,350 --> 00:15:04,230
loop protection because they
keep conversational follow-up

205
00:15:04,230 --> 00:15:07,130
bursts from turning into
uncontrolled backend activity.

206
00:15:10,829 --> 00:15:15,250
Useful error responses are not the
same thing as operational telemetry.

207
00:15:16,469 --> 00:15:20,049
For version one, I kept the
operational surface small but visible.

208
00:15:21,119 --> 00:15:24,890
The server records useful startup
information, such as auth mode,

209
00:15:25,039 --> 00:15:26,709
mutation flag state, and tool count.

210
00:15:28,269 --> 00:15:31,660
It also had type GraphQL errors
and explicit rate limit errors.

211
00:15:33,580 --> 00:15:37,959
Per-tool request logs, latency,
input shape, output, and, and

212
00:15:37,959 --> 00:15:39,269
error type are next layer.

213
00:15:40,379 --> 00:15:45,110
I would add those before expanding
the number of write-capable workflows

214
00:15:45,390 --> 00:15:49,549
because they make it easier to understand
how the MCP layer behaves over time.

215
00:15:51,329 --> 00:15:55,529
This is especially important because
the MCP server is not just transport.

216
00:15:56,340 --> 00:16:00,290
I-if it shapes user-facing behavior,
you need to be able to see what it does.

217
00:16:04,640 --> 00:16:07,620
The recommendation from
these projects are practical.

218
00:16:08,450 --> 00:16:11,630
Start by assuming the MCP layer
is a first-class interface.

219
00:16:11,850 --> 00:16:13,039
Design narrow tools.

220
00:16:13,480 --> 00:16:15,470
Separate read and write behavior early.

221
00:16:16,420 --> 00:16:20,770
Resist optimizing first for flexibility,
because broad, flexible tools are

222
00:16:20,770 --> 00:16:22,620
harder to validate and easier to misuse.

223
00:16:24,740 --> 00:16:26,230
Block mutations by default.

224
00:16:26,400 --> 00:16:28,659
Keep authentication inside
the server boundary.

225
00:16:29,190 --> 00:16:32,330
Validate with mocks, then
validate with real backend.

226
00:16:33,099 --> 00:16:35,730
And treat logging and
auditability as a baseline

227
00:16:35,730 --> 00:16:37,509
requirements, not optional polish.

228
00:16:39,259 --> 00:16:42,210
The main lesson is that
production-friendly MCP work is less

229
00:16:42,210 --> 00:16:45,839
about exposing many capabilities
quickly and more about preserving

230
00:16:45,839 --> 00:16:48,509
clear contracts as capabilities grow.

231
00:16:51,789 --> 00:16:54,339
To close the path, I would
recommend this simple.

232
00:16:56,090 --> 00:16:57,840
Start with one narrow read tool.

233
00:16:57,929 --> 00:16:59,819
Make the input contract explicit.

234
00:17:00,019 --> 00:17:03,489
Add one default deny mutation
only when the read paths are

235
00:17:03,489 --> 00:17:05,340
already as understandable.

236
00:17:06,250 --> 00:17:09,639
Test the actual request shape,
not only the final response.

237
00:17:10,110 --> 00:17:13,049
Then validate the real backend
before connecting the LLM client.

238
00:17:13,809 --> 00:17:15,489
For me, the core lesson is this.

239
00:17:15,629 --> 00:17:19,250
Make the interface narrow,
observable, testable, and safe

240
00:17:19,250 --> 00:17:20,459
enough for real workflows.

241
00:17:21,319 --> 00:17:25,019
This is what turns an- the MCP
server for a d- from a demo wrapper

242
00:17:25,019 --> 00:17:26,539
into a production interface.

243
00:17:27,190 --> 00:17:27,719
Thank you.

